    summary: "A bishop on his way to martyrdom around the year 107 left us some of the earliest words on the Eucharist and the Church.",
    formationText: "Saint Ignatius of Antioch was a bishop and a disciple of the apostles. As Roman soldiers led him to his death in the year 107, he wrote letters to Christian communities that we still read today. In them he calls the Eucharist the flesh of our Savior Jesus Christ, and he urges the faithful to remain united around their bishop and the one altar.\n\nThese letters are precious. They show that the earliest Christians, taught directly by the apostles' generation, already believed in the Real Presence and in the ordered, visible Church we know. The Catholic faith we hold today is not a distortion of the early Church. It is the early Church, handed faithfully down to us.",
